  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real, tangible barrier that affects anyone who feels their identity might be judged through their academic or professional choices. Growing up in Milan with a vocational diploma and parents who only completed lower secondary and primary education, I've seen firsthand how the pressure to conform to stereotypes about who 'belongs' in technical fields can be overwhelming. For instance, when I was younger, I'd avoid math problems because I'd worry about being labeled as 'not smart enough,' even though I loved solving puzzles. This fear isn't unique to any one group; it's a universal experience when someone's self-worth is tied to a stereotype they might internalize. In today's world, where social media amplifies comparisons and perceptions, it's crucial to address this issue without overcomplicating it. I believe the key lies in creating environments where students feel safe to explore their interests without fear of judgment. For example, in my volunteer work with youth groups, I've noticed that when we focus on collaborative projects and celebrate diverse strengths, confidence naturally grows. We shouldn't wait for a perfect solution—small, consistent efforts matter more than grand gestures. It's about nurturing a mindset where everyone feels they belong, regardless of their background. After all, in a world that often tells us we're 'not enough,' the real challenge is helping people believe they are capable of achieving more than they think.",
